Class MappedMinPriorityQueue<E,P>

  • Object
    • MappedMinPriorityQueue<E,P>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - Type of an element in the queue, which should be usable as a Map key
    P - Type representing the priority of an element

    public class MappedMinPriorityQueue<E,P>
extends Object
    A min priority queue that maps each element to a priority. Does not allow duplicate elements, where two elements are considered duplicates if they are equal according to Objects.equals(Object, Object). The elements are ordered according to the order of their priorities, which is specified at construction-time by a Comparator and may be updated dynamically via decrease(Object,Object).
    API Note:
    The distinction between an element and its priority (i.e. what I am calling a "mapped" priority queue here) is intended to make it easier to use and safely implement the decrease key operation. However, this type of mapped queue is uncommon in library code, as few library-based priority queue implementations provide an operation like decrease key in the first place.
    Implementation Requirements:
    You may choose which underlying "concrete" data structure to implement (e.g. binary heap, fibonacci heap, etc.). You may also use (almost) any class found in the Java Collections Library, i.e. the java.util package. The only thing you cannot use are library implementations of a priority queue (e.g. you may not use PriorityQueue).
    Implementation Note:
    Most of the code for this class may be drawn from the slides and the textbook. The hard parts will be the decrease(Object,Object) method and how to internally store the elements and their priorities. Depending on your choice of heap and storage architecture, you may or may not need more than one internal data structure and/or need to create some nested class. You might find HashMap useful.

    • Constructor Detail

      • MappedMinPriorityQueue

        public MappedMinPriorityQueue(Comparator<P> priorityComparator)
        Constructs a new, empty MappedMinPriorityQueue that orders priorities according to the given comparator.

        Comparator.naturalOrder() may be used only if K implements Comparable. Moreover, any priority comparator must entail a total ordering over its domain. However, these two restrictions are not enforced at construction-time.

        Parameters:
        priorityComparator - The comparator used to order the priorities
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - If the priority comparator is null
        See Also:
        Comparator, Comparable

    • Method Detail

      • add

        public boolean add(E element,
                   P priority)
        Adds the specified element to the queue with the given priority iff the element is not already present. More formally, adds the specified element iff the queue contains no element containedElem such that element.equals(containedElem).

        Returns whether the queue did not already contain the specified element.

        Parameters:
        element - The element to add to the queue
        priority - The priority to associate with element
        Returns:
        true iff the queue did not already contain element
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - If any argument is null

      • decrease

        public boolean decrease(E element,
                        P newPriority)
        Updates the priority of the specified element to the given priority iff the new priority is less than the old priority. Returns whether the new priority is less than the old priority.
        Parameters:
        element - The element whose priority is to be decreased
        newPriority - The new priority to associate with element
        Returns:
        true iff the new priority is less than the old priority
        Throws:
        NoSuchElementException - If the element does not exist in the queue
        NullPointerException - If any argument is null
        Implementation Requirements:
        Input validation should be performed in order of nullity check, then existential check.
